# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: danish-crown-company
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] The name Aabenraa originally meant "open beach" (Danish: *åben strand*).
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] Aabenraa was first mentioned in historic accounts in the 12th century, when it was attacked by the Wends.
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] Aabenraa started growing in the early Middle Ages around Opnør Hus, the bishop's castle, and received status as a merchant town in 1240, and in 1335 it received a charter.
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] During the Middle Ages the town was known for its fishing industry and for its production of hops.
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] Between 1560 and 1721, the town was under the rule of the Dukes of Holstein-Gottorp.
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] The town's glory days were during the period of the 1750s to c.
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] 1864, when ship traffic was at a high growth rate with trade to the Mediterranean Sea, China, South America, and Australia.
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] It possessed a good harbour, which afforded shelter for a large carrying trade, Aabenraa having the Danish monarchy's third-largest trade fleet, after Copenhagen and Flensborg.
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] The city had a number of shipbuilding yards, which were known for their fine ships.
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] The best known being the clipper *Cimber*, which in 1857 sailed from Liverpool to San Francisco in 106 days.
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] Fishing and various small factories also provided occupations for the population.
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] From 1864 as a result of the Second War of Schleswig it was part of Prussia, and as such part of the North German Confederation, and from 1871 onwards, part of the German Empire.
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] In the 1920 Schleswig Plebiscite that brought Northern Schleswig to Denmark, 55.1% of Aabenraa's inhabitants voted for remaining part of Germany and 44.9% voted for the cession to Denmark.
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] However, since a plurality of votes in the surrounding Aabenraa municipality voted to join Denmark, the town was thus ceded to the Danish crown.
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] After the 1948 Danish spelling reform, which abolished the digraph Aa in favor of Å, there was fervent resistance in Aabenraa.
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] The town feared, among other things, losing its status as first in alphabetical listings (and reputedly the first town alphabetically anywhere in the world), because the letter *Å* is the last letter in the Dano-Norwegian alphabet.
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] A later revision of the spelling rules allowed for retaining the Aa spelling as an option.
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] While the municipality of Aabenraa and most local citizens use the Aa spelling, Åbenrå remains the option recommended by the Danish Language Board.
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] On June 14, 2019, a low-end IF2/F2/T4 tornado touched down in Aabenraa.
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] Two vehicles were flipped on the local hospital's parking lot.
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] Another primarily rated High-end IF1/F1/T3 tornado struck åbenrå on July 13, 2023, causing moderate damage.
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] Some trees were downed & some buildings were damaged, including one commercial building that had its roof severely blown away.
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] 6 cars were damaged with one being moved 50 Centimetres.
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] The town has a 7.5-meter-deep (25 ft) harbour, with a significant shipping trade.
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] There are various industries in the city, including Marcussen's Organ Building (*Marcussens Orgelbyggeri*) and Callesens Machineworks (*Callesens Maskinfabrik*).
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] The city is the administrative centre for the county.
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] Danmarks Radio has an office in the city.
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] A German minority lives in Aabenraa, and they publish *Der Nordschleswiger* newspaper in German.
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] Some noteworthy buildings in the town are St.
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] Nicholas Church (*Sankt Nicolai Kirke*) from the time of King Valdemar with construction beginning ca.
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] Brundlund Castle (*Brundlund Slot*), erected by Queen Margaret I in 1411, and rebuilt in 1807, today is home to the Brundlund Slot Art Museum (*Kunstmuseet Brundlund Slot*).
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] The town is a bathing resort, as is Elisenlund close by.
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] The city has several preserved neighborhoods from the 1800s including *Slotsgade*, *Store Pottergade*, *Lille Pottergade*, *Nygade*, *Nybro*, *Skibbrogade* and *Gildegade*.
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] A branch of University College South (Danish: *University College Syd*) can be found in Aabenraa.
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] The Port of Aabenraa is the only remaining active commercial port in Southern Jutland.
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] With a depth of 18 metres, it is the deepest port in the eastern part of the Baltic Sea.
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] Aabenraa is located close to the European route E45 motorway.
[src:danish-crown-company/aabenraa] The nearest railway station is Rødekro railway station which is located on the Fredericia–Padborg railway line c.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] By road Aalborg is 64 kilometres (40 mi) southwest of Frederikshavn, and 118 kilometres (73 mi) north of Aarhus.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The distance to Copenhagen is 412 kilometres (256 mi) by road without using ferries.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The earliest settlements date to around AD 700.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Aalborg's position at the narrowest point on the Limfjord made it an important harbour during the Middle Ages, and later a large industrial centre.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Architecturally, the city is known for its half-timbered mansions built by its prosperous merchants.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Budolfi Church, now a cathedral, dates from the end of the 14th century and Aalborghus Castle, a royal residence, was built in 1550.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Today, Aalborg is a city in transition from a working-class industrial area to a knowledge-based community.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] A major exporter of grain, cement, and liquors, its business interests include Siemens Gamesa Renewable Energy, Alfa Laval, and Aalborg Portland.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] These companies have become global producers of wind turbine rotors, marine boilers, and cement.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] With its theatres, symphony orchestra, opera company, performance venues, and museums such as Aalborg Historical Museum and the Aalborg Museum of Modern Art, Aalborg is an important cultural hub.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The Aalborg Carnival, held at the end of May, is one of the largest festivals in Scandinavia, attracting some 100,000+ people annually.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The town's major university is Aalborg University (often abbreviated to AAU), founded in 1974, which has more than 20,000 students (as of 2018).
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] AAU is also North Jutland's largest university.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The University College of Northern Denmark (UCN) is one of seven new regional organisations while the Royal School of Library and Information Science (RSLIS) provides higher education in library and information science.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Trænregimentet, the Danish regiment for army supply and emergency medical personnel, is also in Aalborg.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Aalborg University Hospital, the largest in the north of Jutland, was founded in 1881.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The football club Aalborg BK, established in 1885 and based at Nordjyske Arena, won the Danish Superliga in the 1994–95 season, the 1998–99 season, the 2007–08 season, and the 2013–14 season.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Other sports associations include the ice hockey club Aalborg Pirates, the men's handball team Aalborg Håndbold, the rugby club Aalborg RK, and Aalborg Cricket Club.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Kennedys Plads has connected the city to Randers and the south since 1869.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Aalborg Airport is just 6 kilometres (3.7 mi) northwest of the city centre.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] A 2014 survey by the European Commission found that the citizens of Aalborg are the most satisfied people in Europe with their city.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The name of Aalborg can be traced back to coins from the 11th century in the form of *Alabu* or *Alabur*.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Like Aabenraa, there has been dissent regarding the spelling of the city's name.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] In current times, the modern name of Aalborg is nearly always written with a double-a instead of the Danish standard letter for that sound, å. Å was implemented to replace "aa" in all Danish place names on 22 March 1948 as a result of a Danish spelling reform.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] In 1984, then Minister of Education Bertel Haarder and Minister of Culture Mimi Jakobsen, decided that the municipalities of Denmark could decide for themselves which way of spelling they preferred.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] This went against the Danish Language Council and the Toponomy Committee's advice.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Both spellings are included in the official list of placenames.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] It is never orthographically wrong to write Ålborg though it might upset local residents, many of whom identify strongly with the traditional spelling of the name.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Aalborg is locally known as "Dobbelt A" (*Double A*) and the local rapper Niarn has even made a song about the city of the same name.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The city has also been nicknamed "Nordens Paris" (*Paris of the North*).
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The area around the narrowest point on the Limfjord attracted settlements as far back as the Iron Age, leading to a thriving Viking community until around the year 1000 in what has now become Aalborg.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] In the Middle Ages, the town grew thanks to royal trading privileges, a natural harbour and a thriving herring fishing industry.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The following centuries brought difficulties, but the city began to prosper again towards the end of the 19th century when a bridge was built over Limfjord and the railway arrived.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Aalborg's initial growth relied on heavy industry but its current development focuses on culture and education.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Aalborg traces its history back over a thousand years.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] It was originally settled as a trading post because of its position on the Limfjord.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The sites of what were two settlements and a burial ground can be seen on Lindholm Høje, a hill overlooking the city.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] These large settlements, one from the sixth-century Germanic Iron Age, the other from the Viking Age in the 9th to 11th centuries, evolved at the narrowest point on Limfjord as a result of the traffic between Himmerland to the south and Vendsyssel to the north.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The first mention of Aalborg under its original name *Alabu* or *Alabur* on coins from c.1040 when King Harthacnut (Hardeknud) settled in the area.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] In c.1075, Adam of Bremen reported that *Alaburg*, as he called it in German, was an important harbour for ships sailing to Norway.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] In Valdemar's Danish Census Book from 1231 it was called *Aleburgh*, possibly meaning "the fort by the stream" as in Old Norse *all* meant "stream" or "current" and *bur* or *burgh* a fort or a castle.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The Church of Our Lady in Aalborg was built in the early 12th century but demolished during the Reformation.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Similarly, Tthe Franciscan friary, or Greyfriars, on the east side of Østerå, was probably built around 1240; it was documented in 1268, but like many other Roman Catholic monasteries and convents was shut down in 1530 as a result of the Reformation.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Aalborg's earliest trading privileges date from 1342, when King Valdemar IV received the town as part of his huge dowry on marrying Helvig of Schleswig.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The privileges were extended by Eric of Pomerania in 1430 and by Christopher of Bavaria in 1441.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The town prospered, becoming one of the largest communities in Denmark.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Its prosperity increased when the merchant- and trade association Guds Legems Laug was established in 1481, facilitating trade with the Hanseatic League, especially from 1516 when Christian II granted it a monopoly in salting Limfjord's herring.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The king often visited the town, where he held court and stayed in the old Aalborghus.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The herring fishery linked Aalborg to the East coast of England, across the North Sea, both in commercial competition and cultural exchange.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] During the Middle Ages a number of important institutions were established in Aalborg, including Budolfi Cathedral in the late 14th century and the Hospital of the Holy Ghost, a monastery and nunnery founded in 1451 to help those in need.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] It was converted into a hospital during the Reformation and is still in use today as a nursing home for the elderly.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] In 1530 a large part of the town was destroyed by fire, and in December 1534 it was stormed and plundered by the king's troops after a peasants' revolt known as the Count's Feud led by Skipper Clement.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] This caused the death of up to 2,000 people.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The Reformation in 1536 brought about the demolition of the town's two monasteries.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] As a result of the Reformation, Aalborg became a Lutheran bishopric in 1554.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] From the 1550s to the 1640s, thanks increased foreign trade, Aalborg prospered second only to that of Copenhagen.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The population grew and many fine buildings were built thanks to merchant shipping routes from Norway to Portugal.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] As such, by 1644, despite previous occupation by imperial forces from 1627 to 1629, Aalborg was a prosperous town with 3,000 to 5,000 inhabitants and a harbor providing access to the Kattegat, Norway, the Limfjord countryside, and Vendsyssel.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] In 1663, the city suffered another serious fire, which destroyed the tower of Budolfi Church.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] During the second half of the 18th century, Aalborg entered a further period of prosperity.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] In Erik Pontoppidan's *Danske Atlas* (Danish Atlas) it was described as "after Copenhagen, the best and most prosperous market town in Denmark".
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] In 1767, Denmark's second appeared in Aalborg.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] After Denmark ceded Norway to Sweden in 1814, Aalborg lost its role as the country's centre for Norwegian trade.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The herring industry also suffered after as the fish disappeared after the 1825 North Sea storm when the sea breached the Agger Tange (which had linked Thy with the rest of Jutland at the western end of Limfjord).
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The state bankruptcy in 1813 also contributed to widespread poverty in the city.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] In the mid-19th century, Aalborg was overtaken by Aarhus as the largest city in Jutland.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] An upturn came after the pontoon bridge over Limfjord was completed in 1865, the railway reached the city in 1869 and a railway bridge over the sound to Vendsyssel in 1872.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The harbour facilities were also improved, making Aalborg Denmark's second port.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Aalborg became the country's main producer of tobacco products and spirits, followed in the 1890s by fertilisers and cement.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] By 1901, the population had increased to almost 31,500.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Around the start of the 20th century, as a result of decisions taken by the municipality, many of the city's half-timbered houses were torn down.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] They were replaced by hundreds of modern buildings, completely changing the look of the city.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Factories with smoking chimneys became ever more prevalent in the outskirts.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Among the most important were De Danske Spritfabrikker (spirits and liquors), De forenede Textilfabrikker (textiles), the East Asiatic Company (trading), Dansk Eternit (building materials) and C.W.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Obel's tobacco factory (established in 1787).
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Smidth, was one of several cement factories operating in 1913, together employing some 800 workers.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] By the 1930s, Aalborg was being promoted as "Denmark's new centre for industry and workers".
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Replanning continued with additional thoroughfares cutting through the city.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The port facilities were also improved with the help of a dredger and the opening of new docks.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] In 1933, Christian X inaugurated a new bridge over Limfjord to replace the fragile pontoon crossing.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Aalborg Airport, officially opened in 1938 because of the success of the cement industry, had in fact operated flights to Copenhagen since 1936.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] During the German invasion of Denmark in 1940, the airport was captured by German paratroopers on the night of 21 April as a base for German aircraft flying to Norway.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] On 13 August 1940, a dozen Bristol Blenheim bombers of No.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] 82 Squadron RAF were launched against the Luftwaffe airfield during one of the most disastrous Royal Air Force raids of the war.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] One turned back because of fuel problems, but all of the remaining 11 were shot down by enemy fighters and/or flak batteries within 20 minutes.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] After the war, the Royal Air Force destroyed all the German facilities including planes, hangars and equipment but left the passenger facilities intact.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] By 1960, Aalborg had become known as the "city of smoking chimneys", with half of the inhabitants working in industry or manufacturing.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Ten years later, Aalborg's population had grown to around 97,000 inhabitants.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The significance of Aalborg's industry began to decline in the 1970s, precipitating a fall in the city's population until about 1990, when it began to increase again.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] By the year 2000, the service and education sectors accounted for about 60% of the workforce, partly due to the founding of Aalborg University (AAU) in 1974.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Since 1970, Aalborg and the northern suburb of Nørresundby have become a major administrative centre, thanks in part to the offices of the Region Nordjylland established in the east of the city.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] In addition to large industrial companies including Aalborg Portland, the only cement-producing company in the country, and the building products company Eternit, many small and medium-sized enterprises have been established.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The telecommunications and information technology sector has developed with the support of Aalborg University and the North Jutland knowledge park NOVI.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The First European Conference on Sustainable Cities and Towns took place in Aalborg in 1994.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] It adopted the Aalborg Charter, which provides a framework for the delivery of local sustainable development and calls on local authorities to engage in Local Agenda 21 processes.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The Fourth European Sustainable Cities and Towns Conference, held in Aalborg in 2004, adopted the more binding Aalborg Commitments on local sustainable development.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The commitments have now been signed by 650 local authorities while over 2,500 have signed the earlier Aalborg Charter.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] On 10 August 2009, a strong tornado hit downtown Aalborg and some eastern districts.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The tornado severely damaged the rooves of many buildings, snapped and uprooted trees and tossed caravans over hedges along its 6.6 kilometer path.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The European Severe Storms Laboratory *(ESSL)* rated it F2 on the Fujita scale.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Aalborg is in North Jutland (northwestern Denmark), at the narrowest point of the Limfjord, a shallow sound that separates North Jutlandic Island (Vendsyssel-Thy) from the rest of the Jutland Peninsula and connects Aalborg to the Kattegat about 35 kilometres (22 mi) to the east.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Aalborg is 118 km (73 mi) north of Aarhus, 82 km (51 mi) north of Randers, and 64 km (40 mi) southwest of Frederikshavn.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] It is 414 km (257 mi) by Great Belt Fixed Link to Copenhagen, 150 km (93 mi) by the Frederikshavn-Göteborg ferry to Gothenburg in Sweden, and 363 km (226 mi) by the Frederikshavn-Oslo ferry to Oslo in Norway.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The area close to the waterfront is low-lying, with an elevation averaging about 5 metres (16 ft), but there are many hills in and around city, some reaching over 60 m (200 ft).
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Nørresundby, on the northern side of the sound, is also a hilly area.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Villages to the south of Aalborg from west to east include Frejlev, Svenstrup, and Gistrup (which contains extensive woodland to the south as well as a golf club).
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Klarup and Storvorde lie to the southeast along the 595 road, which, flanking a stretch of the Limfjord known as Langerak, leads to the town of Hals.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Nibe, with a harbour on the Limfjord, is 21 kilometres (13 mi) to the southwest, past the village of Frejlev.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The Nibe Broads (Nibe Bredning) in the Limfjord not only has the largest eelgrass belts in Danish waters but is an important sanctuary for thousands of migratory birds.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] To the north of the city, villages include Vadum, Aabybro, Vestbjerg, Sulsted, Tylstrup, Vodskov, and Hjallerup.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] There is an extensive plantation, Branths Plantage - Møgelbjerg, immediately north of Vodskov.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The Himmerland region to the south still has a number of moors which once formed a vast area of heathland extending 35 km (22 mi) to the Rold Forest near Arden.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Rebild Hills in the Rold Forest stretch over 425 acres (172 ha) of rolling heath country about 30 kilometres (19 mi) south of Aalborg.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Lille Vildmose, to the southeast, is reported to be the largest raised bog in north-western Europe.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The city centre, dating from the Middle Ages, lies on a series of clay banks between the former streams of Vesterå and Lilleå, which used to run into the sound.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Despite effective drainage, the main streets, including Algade, still run east to west while the side streets run north to south.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The Budolfi Church and the old town hall line Gammeltorv, the old market square.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The main shopping streets are Algade and Bispengade, the latter lying in between the modern Vesterbro thoroughfare and Nytorv square. Østerågade, once the old harbor, is noted for its merchants' mansions.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The city cemetery, the Kilden park and the modern art museum, Kunsten, are in the modern commercial and administrative area around the railway station to the west.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Beyond this, Hasseris has become a residential district with a number of large villas and detached houses.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The city's main development area is now to the east of the centre although in addition to the university and new areas of housing, it still contains the shipping harbor, Østhavnen, and the cement factory.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The waterfront to the northeast of the centre is being transformed from a harbour into a recreational area with the Utzon Center and Musikkens Hus.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Off the northwestern side of the city in the sound is the island of Egholm, reached via ferry.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The island, with a population of 51 as of 2023, covers an area of 6.05 square kilometres (2.34 sq mi) and consists mainly of farmland although there are still a few untilled areas of salt marshes and woodland.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Dikes have been built along the coastline to protect the island from flooding.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The Kronborg Forest on the island, covering an area of 17 hectares (42 acres), was acquired by the municipal government in 1945.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] A restaurant in the vicinity was established in 1918 but rebuilt in 1946 following a fire.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] To the west of Egholm is the smaller uninhabited Fruensholm, and there are also three small islands to the north.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] There are several man-made lakes nearby: Lindholm Kridtgrav lies to the northwest of Skanse Park on the northern side of Limfjord, while Nordens Kridtgrav to the northwest of Mølleparken is on the southern side.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The Aalborg area is one of three in Denmark where chalk deposits are found (the others being Møns Klint and Stevns).
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The largest quarry is at Rørdal in Øster Sundby (6 km (4 mi) to the east of the city centre), while Vokslev (20 km (12 mi) to the west) has also provided chalk.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Clay is also quarried in Østerådalen in the southern outskirts, making the area ideal for cement production.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The 6.5 hectares (16 acres) Østre Anlæg park is one of the oldest in Aalborg, visited by up to 175,000 people a year.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] It was used as a dumping ground in the 1920s before being cleaned up and made into a recreational area in the 1930s and 1940s.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] It contains lawns, flowers, tall trees, bushes, and a lake, overlooked by St.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The lake is on the site of a former clay pit.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Fifty-one species of bird have been recorded in the park.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Lindholm Fjordpark, to the south of the Lindholm's industrial park, forms part of the green sector of the city known as 'Ryåkilen' along the coast of the sound, covering roughly 50 hectares (120 acres).
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Like Østre Anlæg, it once served as a waste site with landfill, and a housing estate was built on its northeastern side.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Its use as a landfill site was gradually discontinued in the 1990s, and in 1996, extensive restoration work began.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Today it has woodlands and open areas with grass and herbaceous vegetation, notably buckthorn.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] It is also a habitat for many species of migratory birds such as pale-bellied brent geese, curlews, and songbirds.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The park is also used by the Nordjysk Windsurfing Club and has a six-hole golf course.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Aalborg has a number of additional civic parks and recreational facilities.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The Aalborg Zoo opened in 1935 and typically houses 1,300 animals of 138 species, including tigers, chimpanzees, zebra, elephants, giraffes, penguins and polar bears.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] It is one of the area's major tourist attractions with over 300,000 visitors a year.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Within the zoo an African savannah has been created where exotic animals are housed.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Aalborg was home to an amusement park, Karolinelund, founded in 1946.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] In 2005, the founding family sold it to an entrepreneur who resold it to the city the following year.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] When the park closed in 2010, it had 17 attractions.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Recently, the city reopened the park to volunteers who wish to return it to operating status.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] It is now open to the public for leisure without rides and attractions.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] It houses Platform4, a non-profit user-driven project-oriented venue that experiments with electronics in combination with artistic genres.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Volunteers often arrange public seminars, exhibitions, films, music concerts, and more which.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Aalborg has a maritime climate (Cfb), just above the humid continental climate classification (Dfb) with short, mild summers and long, moderately cold winters.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Aalborg is cool most of the year, with average high temperatures of around 20 °C (68 °F) and lows of 11 °C (52 °F) during the summer, and average temperatures of −3 to 2 °C (27 to 36 °F) during the coldest months of January and February, rarely dropping below −15 °C (5 °F).
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The warmest months are typically July and August, with an average temperature of 16 °C (61 °F), but by October the temperature averages 9 °C (48 °F).
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] June has the highest number of hours of sunshine on average at 218, closely followed by May and July.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Jensen, a Social Democrat, was the long-serving Mayor of Aalborg from 1998 until 2013.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] He was succeeded by Thomas Kastrup-Larsen, also a Social Democrat, who was elected to the City Council in 1998.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The current mayor is Lasse Frimand Jensen from the Social Democratic Party who was elected on 19 June 2023.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Aalborg City Council consists of 31 members, including a mayor.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] As of September 2013, 11 of the council seats are held by the Social Democratic Party, nine by Venstre, three by the Socialist People's Party, two by the Danish People's Party, and two by the Conservative People's Party, while three members are professed independents.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The council is mandated to hold a minimum of two meetings per month, with meetings of a public forum format.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Aalborg was the largest town in Jutland until it was surpassed by Aarhus in the mid-19th century.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Dramatic growth began in the late 19th century, with an increase from 14,152 in 1880 to 31,457 in 1901.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] By 1930, the population had grown to 59,091, although the figure was boosted by the merging of Nørre Tranders, Rørdal Fabriksby, Øster Sundby, and Øster Uttrup into Aalborg.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] There was a temporary decline in population to 94,994 in 1976 but in 1981, following the incorporation of Nørresundby, it grew to 114,302.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The population has increased steadily since then; according to the census of 1 January 2009, Aalborg had a total of 122,461 inhabitants.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] As of 2021, the town had a total population of 142,561 (118,871 in the city proper and 23,690 in Nørresundby) making it the fourth most populous in Denmark after Copenhagen, Aarhus, and Odense.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Statistics for 2016 showed there were 210,316 people living in the Municipality of Aalborg.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Aalborg is North Jutland's major industrial and commercial centre, exporting grain, cement, and spirits.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Heavy industry was behind the city's prosperity until fairly recently.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Many of the factories have now closed, to be replaced by developments in the knowledge-based and green-energy sectors.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Mobile and wireless communications industries have grown substantially since the 1990s, when the area became known as "Mobilicon Valley".
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Aalborg is now a major producer of rotors for wind turbines, and in 2021, Siemens Gamesa Renewable Energy produced six of the world's first reusable offshore wind turbine blades at its factory in Østhavnen.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] In January 2011, there were some 9,200 enterprises in Aalborg, employing around 109,000 people or approximately 35% of the workforce of the Northern Region.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] In the 2010s, the city is set on increasing its participation in the global economy through both existing companies and new entrants.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Its efforts are focused on four areas: energy and environment, information technology, health support systems and "Arctic business".
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The latter covers trade with Greenland as the Port of Aalborg handles over 60% of all goods shipped to Greenland.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Four harbours dot the waterfront, Marina Fjordparken, Skudehavnen, Vestre Badehavn, and Østre Havn.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Tourism is also growing, with a considerable rise in the number of passengers at Aalborg Airport.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Aalborg Municipality has Denmark's second highest revenue from tourism and is the only municipality in the north of Denmark where overnight stays are increasing.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Telenor Denmark, part of the Norwegian Telenor telecommunications and mobile phone company, has a workforce of about 1,100 in Aalborg, making it one of the city's largest new employers.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Siemens Wind Power has rotor-blade production and testing facilities in Aalborg.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] In 2012 and 2013, there were additions in both areas.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The new testing plant is the world's largest research test centre for wind turbine technology.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] In 2012, the company shipped a record 570 wind turbine blades from the Port of Aalborg, mainly to England and Ireland, up 45% on the previous year.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Aalborg was home to De Danske Spritfabrikker or Danish Distillers (now owned by the Norwegian company Arcus), which produces numerous brands of akvavit, until 2014.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The company is the world's largest akvavit producer and exporter.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Aalborg Industries, the world's largest manufacturer of marine boilers, has been established in Aalborg since the 1920s.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] It has recently expanded into floating production systems for the offshore market.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Employing 2,600 people, in December 2010 it was acquired by the Swedish Alfa Laval, also a specialist in the area.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Aalborg Portland, a subsidiary of the Italian Cementir since 2004, was founded in 1889 with the support of FLSmidth.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Able to draw on the chalk deposits from Rørdal to the east of the city, it rapidly became a major cement producer.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Today it is the world's largest supplier of white cement, which it exports around the globe.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Aalborg has a wide selection of shops and restaurants.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] In the city centre, there are both large department stores and smaller speciality shops.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] One of the largest shopping malls in Denmark, the Aalborg Storcenter, is to the south of the city in Skalborg.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] It has about 75 stores, including a large Bilka supermarket.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The city has over 300 restaurants, catering in Danish, European and Asian dishes.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Notable establishments include *Irish House*, a pub in the 17th-century Jens Olufsen's House.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] While Aalborg is renowned for its alcohol and nightlife, there are also a number of coffee shops.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Aalborg has 12 large hotels, most within walking distance of the city centre.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The Helnan Phønix Hotel is the largest, occupying what was originally built as a lavish private residence in 1783 for a Danish brigadier.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The Chagall was established in the 1950s and has reproductions of Marc Chagall paintings in the rooms.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Other hotels include Radisson Blu Limfjord Hotel, Park Hotel, Cabinn Aalborg, Hotel Hvide Hus, Hotel Krogen and Prinsen Hotel.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Several banks including Danske Bank, Forex, Jyske Bank, Spar Nord and Nordea have branches in Aalborg.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Despite its industrial background and the factories along its waterfront, the city has gained popularity for tourism in recent years, offering a wide variety of attractions and historic buildings in addition to its museums, churches and parks.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Jens Bang's House (Danish: *Jens Bangs Stenhus*), on Østerågade near the old town hall, is one of Denmark's best examples of 17th-century domestic architecture.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Built in 1624 by the Aalborg merchant Jens Bang in the Dutch Renaissance style, the four-story sandstone building is noted for its rising gables and sculpted auricular window decorations.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] For over 300 years, it has housed the city's oldest pharmacy.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Jørgen Olufsen's House (*Jørgen Olufsens Gård*) on Østerågade is Denmark's best preserved merchant's mansion in the Renaissance style.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Built mainly of sandstone in 1616, it also has a half-timbered section.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The style is reminiscent of similar buildings in the north of Germany and in the Netherlands.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Olufsen, Jens Bang's half brother, was a successful merchant and mayor of Aalborg.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] When it was built, the residence with its integrated warehouse was on the Østerå, an inlet from the sound with access for barges.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The old iron bar with a hook for scales can be seen in the portico.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Aalborghus Castle (*Aalborghus Slot*) is a half-timbered building with red-painted woodwork and whitewashed wall panels.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] It was built in the mid-16th century by King Christian III for his vassals who collected taxes and is the only remaining example of its kind in the country.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The park, dungeon and casemates, but not the castle itself, are open to the public in the summer months.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] In the 1950s, the castle was converted into administrative offices.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Aalborg's old city hall in Gammeltorv, in service until 1912, was built in 1762.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] It is now only used for ceremonial and representative purposes.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Designed in the Late Baroque style, the building with its black-glazed tile roof consists of two storeys and a cellar.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The yellow-washed façade is decorated with white pilasters and a frontispiece featuring the Danish coat of arms and a bust of King Frederick V.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] His motto, *Prudentia et Constantia*, is also seen above the main entrance.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The well-preserved door is an example of the Rococo style.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The building was listed by the Danish Heritage Agency in 1918.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Another old building of note is the half-timbered Håndværkerhuset (at Kattesunded 20) from c.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] 1625, which originally housed a number of warehouses.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] It is now used as a centre for arts and crafts.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Finally, the headquarters of Danish Distillers (*De Danske Spritfabrikker*), to the west of the Limfjord Bridge, is noted for its Neoclassical appearance.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Completed in 1931 by the architect Alf Cock-Clausen, it combines functionality with decorative classical symbolism.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Considered a masterpiece of Danish factory design, it is now a Danish National Heritage site.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Jomfru Ane Gade (literally Virgin Anne's Street) is one of the most famous streets in Aalborg if not in Denmark.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Popular for its cafés and restaurants during the day, it is even busier at night with its clubs, discos and bars.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] During the 1990s, the street was infamously a 'hang out' of two biker gangs who were at war for some years all over Scandinavia.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] As the bikers disappeared it became increasingly popular for people of all ages.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The pedestrian hubs of Nytorv Square and John F.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Kennedy Square in the central city area are also part of the cityscape.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Aalborgtårnet is a tripod tower erected in 1933 with a restaurant on the top.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The tower itself is 55 m (180 ft) high; but as it stands on the top of the Skovbakken hill, it reaches a total height of 105 m (344.49 ft) above sea level, providing a view over the sound and the city.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Designed by Carlo Odgård, it was erected in 1933 in connection with the North Jutland Fair.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] In 2008, the Utzon Center, its art, architecture and design credited to the noted architect Jørn Utzon, is also dedicated to him.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] It was built next to the Limfjord at the central harbour front in Aalborg.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Born in Copenhagen, Utzon grew up in Aalborg.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The centre contains an exhibition on Utzon's work, which includes the Sydney Opera House, as well as educational displays on architecture and design.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The centre consists of several individual buildings creating a special place around a courtyard on a platform.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The tall sculptural roofs of the auditorium and the boat-hall, both on the harbour front, and the library facing the park area and the city are set off by the lower roofs of the exhibition and workshop areas inside the complex.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The annual Aalborg Carnival usually takes place in the last weekend of May.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] It consists of three events: the children's carnival (Danish: *Børnekarneval*), the battle of carnival bands, and the carnival proper.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Attracting about 100,000 visitors, it is the biggest carnival in Scandinavia and one of the largest in northern Europe.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Hjallerup Market in Hjallerup, about 20 kilometres (12 mi) northeast of Aalborg is one of the oldest and largest markets in Denmark and is the largest horse market in Europe.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Held for three days in the beginning of June, it annually attracts more than 200,000 people and 1200 horses.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] In 1999, Aalborg was for the first time one of the four host ports in The Tall Ships Race (then Cutty Sark Tall Ships Race) of that year.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The city hosted the world's largest event for sailing vessels again in 2004, 2010, and 2015.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Aalborgs Kongres & Kultur Center, designed in a functional style by Otto Frankild, was completed in 1952.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The centre's main component, the Aalborg Hall, can be divided into sections.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The complex also contains a hotel, restaurant, bowling alley, and a number of meeting rooms.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The smaller Europahallen was added in 1991, making the centre the largest in Scandinavia.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] With over 100 theatrical and musical presentations per year, it offers international stars, opera, ballet, musicals, classical concerts, productions for children as well as pop and rock concerts.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] It can accommodate audiences of up to 2,500.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Aalborg Teater, built in 1878 and subsequently modified by Julius Petersen, seats 870 in the main auditorium.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] First privately owned, the theatre is now controlled and owned by the Danish Ministry of Culture.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] While most productions are housed in the main hall, the building can accommodate up to four shows at once in halls of varying sizes.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Over the years, the theatre has produced a wide selection of drama and musicals.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Nordkraft is a cultural centre in a former power plant near the harbour.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] It has theatres, a cinema, and concert facilities.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Kunsthal Nord, established in the centre in 2009, arranges up to five exhibitions a year of all forms of contemporary art, especially of local origin but also from other parts of Denmark and beyond.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] It serves as the exhibition centre for KunstVærket, the North Jutland centre for the arts, and also works in collaboration with the modern art museum Kunsten designed by the Finnish architect Alvar Aalto.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] In the same neighbourhood, a huge concert hall, Musikkens Hus, designed by Coop Himmelb(l)au, opened in 2014.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] It is Aalborg's most ambitious construction project in recent years.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The city also has a wide selection of galleries and arts and crafts outlets operated by local artists.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The Academy of Music also has a presence in Aarhus.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] There are several glass workshops; others produce jewelry, sculptures or exhibit paintings.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The Aalborg Historical Museum was established in 1863, making it one of the earliest provincial museums in the country.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The North Jutland Historical Museum conducted a series of archaeological excavations in the 1950s at Lindholm Høje, revealing ancient burial sites.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] In 1992, the Lindholm Høje Museum was opened there and extended in 2008.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] In 1994 and 1995, excavations at the site of the Greyfriars Monastery resulted in the creation of the underground Gråbrødrekloster Museum in the city centre.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Several organisations now collaborate under the leadership of the North Jutland Historical Museum.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The Springeren - Marine Experience Center is a marine museum on the city's wharf with a wide range of exhibits including "Springeren", an old Danish submarine, whence its name.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The Aalborg Defence and Garrison Museum documents Danish defences during the Second World War as well as the history of Aaborg's garrison since 1779.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The KUNSTEN Museum of Modern Art Aalborg was built from 1958 to 1972; the collection consists of around 1,500 art objects, including paintings, sculptures and other media.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The Aalborg Symphony Orchestra (Danish: *Aalborg Symfoniorkester*) founded in 1943 presents about 150 concerts a year, frequently playing in the Musikkens Hus.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] It also plays for the Jutland opera company (Danish: *Den Jyske Opera*, also based in Aalborg), and at the Royal Danish Theatre in Copenhagen.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] It is one of the main organisers of the 10-day Aalborg Opera Festival held every March.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Aalborg has the jazz club Jazzclub Satchmo and an annual jazz and blues festival (Danish: *Den Blå Festival*), also known as the Mini New Orleans Festival.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Over four days in mid-August, concerts are performed on squares, in the streets, and in cafés and restaurants.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Since 2012, the Egholm Festival, a small music festival on the island of Egholm near Aalborg has been organized in the first weekend of August.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The principal religion in Aalborg as in the rest of Denmark is Christianity.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Aalborg is the seat of a bishop within the Lutheran State Church of Denmark.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The cathedral of this bishopric is the Budolfi Church, originally built no later than 1132 by Viborg's Bishop Eskil.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] This church was considerably smaller than the current one, as it was merely a parish church.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The existing structure was completed in the late 14th century, on the grounds of the former church, and was listed for the first time in the Atlas of Denmark in 1399.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The church was named after St Botolph, an English abbot and saint.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The church is constructed in the Gothic style.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] In 1554 Aalborg was made a diocese and, after consideration, St Budolfi Church was made the seat of the Bishop of Aalborg.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Aalborg is also home to the former Catholic church, the Abbey of Our Lady, converted from a Benedictine nunnery.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The present Budolfi Church, which has the status of a cathedral, dates from the end of the 14th century, although at least two earlier churches stood on the same spot.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Built in the Gothic style, it consists of a nave flanked by two aisles, a tower, and a porch.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] After the original tower was destroyed by fire in 1663, the striking new Baroque tower, based on that of an earlier Copenhagen city hall, was completed in 1779.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The church has 16th-century frescoes and an intricately carved early Baroque altarpiece from 1689 created by Lauridtz Jensen.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Abbey of Our Lady (*Vor Frue Kirke*) was designed in 1878 by J.E.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The original Church of Our Lady from the early 12th century was pulled down after the Reformation because it was old and unstable, but the 12th-century tower and the original portal with sculpted decorations can still be seen.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] As a result of the considerable population increase from the end of the 19th century, a number of new churches were built in various styles.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Next to Aalborg Hall, Ansgar's Church with its tall tower was built in 1929 to a design by Hother August Paludan in a modern Baroque style.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] St Mark's Church (*Sankt Markus Kirke*), completed in 1933, was designed by Einar Packness.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Its tower is crowned by an imposing spire.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The Biblical figures known as the Johannes Group (based on Christ's meeting with John the Baptist in Matthew, Chapter 3) sculpted by Bertel Thorvaldsen are displayed around the interior.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The Margrethe Church with its steeply sloping roof reaching 22 m (72 ft) is the work of Carlo Odgaard and Aaby Sørensen.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Bent Exner designed some of the artefacts in the church including the crucifix over the altar.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Aalborg's cemeteries have a history dating to the end of the Middle Ages.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Sankt Jørgens Kirkegård (St George's Cemetery) was on the corner of Hasserisgade and Kirkegårdsgade.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The site was chosen in a district outside the city as it provided isolation for those affected by the plague, many of whom died in the neighbouring hospice, Sankt Jørgens Gårde.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] In 1794, a new cemetery was opened in Klostermarken, immediately to the south of Sankt Jørgens Kirkegård.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] It is now known as Aalborgs Almen Kirkegård (meaning "common cemetery") and contains the graves of many of the city's most notable citizens.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Aalborg had a synagogue, built in 1854; and the Jewish rabbi Salomon Mielziner served it for 35 years.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Services were no longer offered after Mielziner died, and in 1924 the synagogue was donated to the city government, which began using it to store the city archives (Stadsarkivet).
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] It was burned down by the Schalburg Corps in April 1945 towards the end of World War II, destroying its centuries-old Torahs.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] Antisemitism continues to exist in Denmark, and in 1999, an unlicensed Nazi radio station began operating from a neo-Nazi stronghold in Fynen, Nørresundby, within Aalborg municipality.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p01] The activity has been widely denounced with organized opposition in Aalborg and the rest of Denmark, and in February 1999, 12 anti-fascists were arrested for possession of explosives at their base in Fynen.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] Aalborg University (AAU), Campus East, as seen during summertime.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] Boulevarden in Aalborg's town centre, seen in 2011.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] The major university in Aalborg is the University of Aalborg (AAU), founded in 1974.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] It has more than 17,000 students and more than 3,000 employees.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] In 2012, 3,000 new students started at the university.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] In 1995 it merged with Esbjerg Engineering College.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] The university has attempted from the outset to "develop a more "relevant" form of education than was then being offered by the established universities".
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] It has sought to develop what is known as "contextual knowledge", a form of problem-based learning based around the project work conducted by students, rather than the curriculum focusing on traditional academic disciplines.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] The University College of Northern Denmark is one of seven new regional organisations (*professionshøjskoler*) of different study sites in Denmark offering courses normally at the bachelor level.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] The Royal School of Library and Information Science (RSLIS) provides higher education in library and information science; one of its two departments is in Aalborg.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] With about 4,500 students a year and 700 employees, Tech College Aalborg offers a wide spectrum of vocational training and runs Aalborg Tekniske Gymnasium.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] Aalborg Business College provides basic training in retail and trading for private enterprises and the public sector, with courses which cover information technology, economics, sales and communication, and languages.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] The island of Egholm contains the former Egholm Skole, which was closed in 1972 when a ferry service to Aalborg was established and children on the island began attending the Vesterkæret Skole in Aalborg.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] Today the old school on Egholm is run as a school camp by the City of Aalborg, with 18 beds and facilities for 60 people.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] Skipper Clement International School is a private school for children between 6 and 16.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] The international department conducts its classes in both Danish and English, the first to be established in the Jutland peninsula.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] The city is home to Aalborg BK, established in 1885 and known as "AaB" for short.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] The club has won the Danish championship (Superliga) four times in recent years; 1995, 1999, 2008 and 2014.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] The team qualified for the group stages of the 1995–96 and 2008–09 UEFA Champions League seasons.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] Aalborg Chang is a Danish amateur association football club, previously known as FC Nordjylland.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] Aalborg is also known for the women's handball club Aalborg DH, and the men's handball club Aalborg Håndbold.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] Established in 2001 and 2011, respectively, they both play their games in the Gigantium.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] Rugby in Aalborg is represented by Aalborg RK *Lynet* (Lightning), established in 1964.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] The city also has the Aalborg Cricket Club, which is part of the Danish Cricket League.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] They were established in 2000 and have players from various nations.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] Aalborg Tennisklub is located along the Kastetvej road in the centre of Aalborg.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] About 10 kilometres (6.2 mi) to the southwest of the city, near the hamlet of Restrup Enge, is Aalborg Golf Klub.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] Aalborg Golf Klub is the second oldest golf club in Denmark, and was originally established in 1908 in the eastern part of Aalborg.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] In 1929 it moved to Sohngaardsholm, but 30 years later the course had to again move because of developments with the university.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] The present course to the southwest of Aalborg was designed in 1968 by Graham Lockey and Commander John Harris as a 9-hole course, later expanded to 18 holes in 1976 and 27 in 2006.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] In 2010 the club hosted the European Girls Team Golf Championships.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] Another course, Ørnehoj Golfklub, is at the southeastern limits of the city, in the village of Gistrup.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] On 11 September 1977, Aalborg hosted the Final of the Long Track World Championship for Motorcycle speedway, which was won by Swedish rider Anders Michanek.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] On the north side of the Limfjord is Nørresundby, connected to Aalborg by the Limfjordsbroen road bridge, which was inaugurated in 1933, replacing a pontoon bridge which dated to 1865.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] The iron Limfjord Railway Bridge, inaugurated in 1938, is a nine-span bascule bridge.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] It opens 4,000 times a year, allowing around 10,000 vessels to sail under it.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] Opening in 1969 as the first motorway tunnel to be built in Denmark, the Limfjord Tunnel is 582 m (1,909 ft) long and has three lanes in each direction.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] It forms part of the E45, stretching from Alta, Norway, to Gela, Italy.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] Aalborg Airport is 6 kilometres (3.7 mi) northwest of the city centre.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] With its two runways, it has 20 direct routes to destinations in Denmark, Norway, the Netherlands, the UK, Spain, and Turkey, along with seasonal flights to additional Spanish destinations and the Faroe Islands.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] Processing 1.4 million passengers a year, the airport is the third largest in Denmark.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] The Aalborg Air Base, an important Danish Air Force facility, occupies part of the extensive airport area.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] The Port of Aalborg is northern Denmark's main import/export hub, operated by Aalborg Havn A/S on the Limfjord.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] Two additional private harbours serve the cement factory, Aalborg Portland A/S, and the power station, Vattenfall A/S.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] The city's main train station, Aalborg Railway Station, is on John F.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] It opened in 1869, when the Aalborg to Randers railway line was inaugurated.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] The original station building was designed by N.P.C.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] Holsøe while the present building, which opened in 1902, was designed by Thomas Arboe.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] Aalborg Railway Station is operated by Banedanmark and the railway companies DSB and Nordjyske Jernbaner.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] Other rail stations in Aalborg are Skalborg Station, Aalborg Vestby Station and Lindholm Station.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] There are regular bus services covering the inner city as well as the wider urban area.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] In 2008, plans were made to build a light rail system to serve Aalborg, similar to Odense Letbane and Aarhus Letbane.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] In 2014, the government committed funding to light rail in Aalborg, only to retract the funding after a Venstre-led cabinet was elected in the 2015 general election, replacing the Social Democrat-led government that had approved the funds.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] In 2017, government funding was approved to build a bus rapid transit system instead of the light rail.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] The system known as Plusbus eventually opened on 23 September 2023.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] Cycling is also relatively popular in Aalborg.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] Statistics for 2012 indicate 44% of the population use their bicycles several times a week while 27% of the workforce cycle to work.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] The municipal authorities hope to increase the use of bicycles by providing better cycle tracks and parking facilities, as well as improved support services.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] Starting from 2009, city bikes were provided free of charge in Aalborg and Nørresundby from April to November with numerous stands throughout the area, however the city bike system was closed down in 2014 when funding ran out.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] As of 2013, it consists of two large buildings in Aalborg, the hospital in Dronninglund and smaller departments in Hobro and Hjørring.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] It is the largest employer in the area with around 6,500 on the payroll.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] The hospital has traditionally undertaken research but from the beginning of 2013 it has had a formal collaboration with Aalborg University.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] A new building, designed by schmidt hammer lassen architects and to be completed by 2020, will provide 134,000 m2 (1,440,000 sq ft) for hospital buildings and 17,000 m2 (180,000 sq ft) for the university's Faculty of Health.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] The Aalborg University Hospital, section south, is on Hobrovej and has a 24-hour emergency ward.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] The northern section is in Reberbanegade, which is in the western part of the city centre.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] ANR (also Aalborg Nærradio and Alle Nordjyders Radio) is a local radio station operated by Nordjyske Medier, owner of *Nordjyske Stiftstidende*.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] The TV news channel, 24Nordjyske, is operated by the same firm.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] Among those who contributed to Aalborg's prosperity in the 19th century were Poul Pagh (1796–1870) who significantly developed trade and shipping, and Christen Winther Obel (1800–1860) who increased production at the C.W.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] Obel tobacco factory until it became the city's main employer.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] Another important figure of the times was Marie Rée (1835–1900) who ran the local newspaper *Aalborg Stiftstidende* until 1900, often promoting women's rights.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] More recently, the actor and script-writer Preben Kaas (1930–1981), who was born in Aalborg, starred in over 50 Danish films.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] Among the city's many sporting figures, Peter Gade (born 1976) stands out as one of the world's most successful badminton players.
[src:danish-crown-company/aalborg-p02] On the cultural side, Jørn Utzon (1918–2008), designer of the Sydney Opera House, grew up in Aalborg; the iconic Utzon Center which he inspired now serves as a museum for his architectural designs and offers courses of study based on his approach.
[src:danish-crown-company/aktieselskab] The term *aktieselskab* may be abbreviated AS, ⁠A/S⁠, A⁄S, A/S, a/s, or various other orthographic stylizations along the same lines.
[src:danish-crown-company/aktieselskab] **⅍** (U+214D ⅍ AKTIESELSKAB) is a dedicated Unicode character for this abbreviation; not to be confused with the similar-but-distinct U+2101 ℁ ADDRESSED TO THE SUBJECT.
[src:danish-crown-company/aktieselskab] This abbreviation is pronounced [ˈɛˀ ˈes].
[src:danish-crown-company/aktieselskab] The shareholders of an *aktieselskab* are not liable for the debts of the company.
[src:danish-crown-company/aktieselskab] If an A/S is owned by a holding company (typically another A/S or ApS), the profit from the production company can be transferred to the holding company and the two will be taxed as if they were one entity (*sambeskatning*; joint taxation).
[src:danish-crown-company/aktieselskab] Both an *aktieselskab* (A/S) and an *anpartselskab* (ApS) are by definition, limited liability companies; the main difference being that only the A/S issues stock.
[src:danish-crown-company/aktieselskab] In case of bankruptcy, creditors are not able to pursue claims towards investors who have not personally provided security.
[src:danish-crown-company/aktieselskab] Professional credit lenders such as banks will consequently demand security for credit lend to the A/S or ApS since securitized debt are given legal preference compared to unsecured debts.
[src:danish-crown-company/aktieselskab] This power is vested in *Konkursloven* [Bankruptcy Law] articles 64-81.
[src:danish-crown-company/aktieselskab] An *aktieselskab* can only acquire rights or incur obligations as a company when it has been registered at the Danish Commerce and Companies Agency.
[src:danish-crown-company/aktieselskab] The share capital registered at the Danish Commerce and Companies Agency must be at least 400,000 DKK.
[src:danish-crown-company/aktieselskab] This amount was changed in 2018 from the previous 500,000 DKK.
[src:danish-crown-company/aktieselskab] The capital can come from contributions of cash or other assets.
[src:danish-crown-company/aktieselskab] If half of the capital is lost, the board of directors must convene a general meeting within six months.
[src:danish-crown-company/aktieselskab] An *aktieselskab* must have a board of directors consisting of at least three members.
[src:danish-crown-company/aktieselskab] Members of the board can be elected for a period of up to four years, depending on the articles of association.
[src:danish-crown-company/aktieselskab] The board members are usually elected at the general meeting.
[src:danish-crown-company/aktieselskab] The articles of association may confer upon public authorities or any third party the right to appoint one or more members of the board of directors.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] In prehistoric times, humans hunted aurochs and later domesticated them.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Since that time, numerous breeds of cattle have been bred specifically for the quality or quantity of their meat.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Today, beef is the third most widely consumed meat in the world, after pork and poultry.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] As of 2018, the United States, Brazil, and China were the largest producers of beef.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Some religions and cultures prohibit beef consumption, especially Indian religions like Hinduism.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Buddhists are also against animal slaughtering, but they do not have a wrongful eating doctrine.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] The word *beef* is from the Latin word *bōs*, in contrast to *cow* which is from Middle English *cou* (both words have the same Indo-European root **gʷou-*).
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] *Beef* is cognate with *bovine* through the Late Latin *bovīnus*.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] The rarely used plural form of beef is *beeves*.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] People have eaten the flesh of bovines since prehistoric times.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] The aurochs, the ancestor of modern domestic cattle, is known to have been hunted and consumed by Neanderthals.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Some of the earliest known cave paintings, such as those of Lascaux, show aurochs in hunting scenes.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] People domesticated cattle to provide ready access to beef, milk, and leather.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Cattle have been domesticated at least twice over the course of evolutionary history.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] The first domestication event occurred around 10,500 years ago with the evolution of *Bos taurus*.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] The second was more recent, around 7,000 years ago, with the evolution of *Bos indicus* in the Indian subcontinent.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] There is a possible third domestication event 8,500 years ago, with a potential third species *Bos africanus* arising in Africa.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] In the United States, the growth of the beef business was largely due to expansion in the Southwest.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Upon the acquisition of grasslands through the Mexican–American War of 1848, and later the expulsion of the Plains Indians from this region and the Midwest, the American livestock industry began, starting primarily with the taming of feral and semi-feral Longhorn cattle.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Chicago and New York City were the first to benefit from these developments in their stockyards and in their meat markets.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Beef cattle are raised and fed using a variety of methods, including feedlots, free range, ranching, backgrounding and intensive animal farming.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Concentrated Animal Feeding Operations (CAFOs), commonly referred to as factory farms, are commonly used to meet the demand of beef production.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] CAFOs supply 70.4% of cows in the US market and 99% of all meat in the United States supply.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Cattle CAFOs can also be a source of *E. coli* contamination in the food supply due to the prevalence of manure in CAFOs.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] These *E. coli* contaminations include one strain, *E. coli* O157:H7, which can be toxic to humans, because cattle typically hold this strain in their digestive system.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Another consequence of unsanitary conditions created by high-density confinement systems is increased use of antibiotics in order to prevent illness.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] An analysis of FDA sales data by the Natural Resources Defense Council found 42% of medically important antibiotic use in the U.S. was on cattle, posing concerns about the development of antibiotic resistant bacteria.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] In 2023 production was forecast to peak by 2035.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] The consumption of beef poses numerous threats to the natural environment.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Of all agricultural products, beef requires some of the most land and water, and its production results in the greatest amount of greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions, air pollution, and water pollution.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] A 2021 study added up GHG emissions from the entire lifecycle, including production, transportation, and consumption, and estimated that beef contributed about 4 billion tonnes (9%) of anthropogenic greenhouse gases in 2010.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Cattle populations graze around 26% of all land on Earth, not including the large agricultural fields that are used to grow cattle feed.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] 91% of Amazon land deforested since 1970 has been converted to cattle ranching.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] 41% of global deforestation from 2005 to 2013 has been attributed to the expansion of beef production.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] This is due to the higher ratio of net energy of gain to net energy of maintenance where metabolizable energy intake is higher.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] The ratio of feed required to produce an equivalent amount of beef (live weight) has been estimated at 7:1 to 43:1, compared with about 2:1 for chicken.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] However, assumptions about feed quality are implicit in such generalizations.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] For example, production of a kilogram of beef cattle live weight may require between 4 and 5 kilograms of feed high in protein and metabolizable energy content, or more than 20 kilograms of feed of much lower quality.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] A simple exchange of beef to soy beans (a common feed source for cattle) in Americans' diets would, according to one estimate, result in meeting between 46 and 74 percent of the reductions needed to meet the 2020 greenhouse gas emission goals of the United States as pledged in 2009.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] A 2021 CSIRO trial concluded that feeding cattle a 3% diet of the seaweed *Asparagopsis taxiformis* could reduce the methane component of their emissions by 80%.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] While such feed options are still experimental, even when looking at the most widely used feeds around the globe, there is high variability in efficiency.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] One study found that shifting compositions of current feeds, production areas, and informed land restoration could enable greenhouse gas emissions reductions of 34–85% annually (612–1,506 MtCO2e yr−1) without increasing costs to global beef production.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Some scientists claim that the demand for beef is contributing to significant biodiversity loss as it is a significant driver of deforestation and habitat destruction; species-rich habitats, such as significant portions of the Amazon region, are being converted to agriculture for meat production.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] The 2019 IPBES *Global Assessment Report on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services* also concurs that the beef industry plays a significant role in biodiversity loss.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Around 25% to nearly 40% of global land surface is being used for livestock farming, which is mostly cattle.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Some countries regulate the marketing and sale of beef by observing criteria post-slaughter and classifying the observed quality of the meat.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] In 2018, the United States, Brazil, and China produced the most beef with 12.22 million tons, 9.9 million tons, and 6.46 million tons respectively.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] The top 3 beef exporting countries in 2019 were Australia (14.8% of total exports), the United States (13.4% of total exports), and Brazil (12.6% of total exports).
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Beef production is also important to the economies of Japan, Argentina, Uruguay, Canada, Paraguay, Mexico, Belarus and Nicaragua.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] As per 2020, Brazil was the largest beef exporter in the world followed by Australia, United States, India (Includes Carabeef only) and Argentina.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Brazil, Australia, the United States and India accounted for roughly 61% of the world's beef exports.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] The world produced 60.57 million metric tons of beef in 2020, down 950K metric tons from the prior year.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Major decline for production of beef was from India up to 510k and Australia down to 309K metric tons from the prior year.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Heatwaves can also reduce milk yield, with particularly acute impacts if the heatwave lasts for four or more days, as at that point the cow's thermoregulation capacity is usually exhausted, and its core body temperature starts to increase.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] At worst, heatwaves can lead to mass mortality: in July 1995, over 4,000 cattle died in the mid-central United States heatwave.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] In 1999, over 5,000 cattle died during a heatwave in northeastern Nebraska.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Studies suggest that Brahman cattle and its cross-breeds are more resistant to heat stress than the regular *bos taurus* breeds, but it is considered unlikely that even more heat-resistant cattle can be bred at a sufficient rate to keep up with the expected warming.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Both male and female cattle can have their reproduction impaired by heat stress.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] In males, severe heat can affect both spermatogenesis and the stored spermatozoa.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] It may take up to eight weeks for sperm to become viable again.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] In females, heat stress negatively affects conception rates as it impairs corpus luteum and thus ovarian function and oocyte quality.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Even after conception, a pregnancy is less likely to be carried to term due to reduced endometrial function and uterine blood flow, leading to increased embryonic mortality and early fetal loss.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Most beef can be used as is by merely cutting into certain parts, such as roasts, short ribs or steak (filet mignon, sirloin steak, rump steak, rib steak, rib eye steak, hanger steak, and others), while other cuts are processed (corned beef or beef jerky).
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Trimmings, on the other hand, which are usually mixed with meat from older, leaner (therefore tougher) cattle, are ground, minced or used in sausages.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] The blood is used in some varieties called blood sausage.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Some intestines are cooked and eaten as is, but are more often cleaned and used as natural sausage casings.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] The bones are used for making beef stock.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Meat from younger cows (calves) is called veal.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Beef from steers and heifers is similar.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Beef is first divided into primal cuts, large pieces of the animal initially separated by butchering.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] These are basic sections from which steaks and other subdivisions are cut.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] The term "primal cut" is quite different from "prime cut", used to characterize cuts considered to be of higher quality.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Since the animal's legs and neck muscles do the most work, they are the toughest; the meat becomes more tender as distance from *hoof and horn* increases.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Different countries and cuisines have different cuts and names, and sometimes use the same name for a different cut; for example, the cut described as "brisket" in the United States is from a significantly different part of the carcass than British brisket.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] To improve tenderness of beef, it is often aged (i.e., stored refrigerated) to allow endogenous proteolytic enzymes to weaken structural and myofibrillar proteins.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Wet aging is accomplished using vacuum packaging to reduce spoilage and yield loss.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Dry aging involves hanging primals (usually ribs or loins) in humidity-controlled coolers.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Outer surfaces dry out and can support growth of molds (and spoilage bacteria, if too humid), resulting in trim and evaporative losses.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Evaporation concentrates the remaining proteins and increases flavor intensity; the molds can contribute a nut-like flavor.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] After two to three days there are significant effects.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] The majority of the tenderizing effect occurs in the first 10 days.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Boxed beef, stored and distributed in vacuum packaging, is, in effect, wet aged during distribution.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Premium steakhouses dry age for 21 to 28 days or wet age up to 45 days for maximum effect on flavor and tenderness.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Meat from less tender cuts or older cattle can be mechanically tenderized by forcing small, sharp blades through the cuts to disrupt the proteins.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Similarly, solutions of salt and sodium phosphates can be injected to soften and swell the myofibrillar proteins.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Salt can improve the flavor, but phosphate can contribute a soapy flavor.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] These methods are applicable to all types of meat and some other foodstuffs.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Beef can be cooked to various degrees, from very rare to well done.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] The degree of cooking corresponds to the temperature in the approximate center of the meat, which can be measured with a meat thermometer.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Meat can be cooked in boiling oil, typically by shallow frying, although deep frying may be used, often for meat enrobed with breadcrumbs as in milanesas or finger steaks.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Larger pieces such as steaks may be cooked this way, or meat may be cut smaller as in stir frying, typically an Asian way of cooking: cooking oil with flavorings such as garlic, ginger and onions is put in a very hot wok.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Then small pieces of meat are added, followed by ingredients which cook more quickly, such as mixed vegetables.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] The dish is ready when the ingredients are 'just cooked'.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Moist heat cooking methods include braising, pot roasting, stewing and sous-vide.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] These techniques are often used for cuts of beef that are tougher, as these longer, lower-temperature cooking methods have time to dissolve connecting tissue which otherwise makes meat remain tough after cooking.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] simmering meat, whole or cut into bite-size pieces, in a water-based liquid with flavorings.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] cooking meats, in a covered container, with small amounts of liquids (usually seasoned or flavored).
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Unlike stewing, braised meat is not fully immersed in liquid, and usually is browned before the oven step.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Sous-vide, French for "under vacuum", is a method of cooking food sealed in airtight plastic bags in a water bath for a long time—72 hours is not unknown—at an accurately determined temperature much lower than normally used for other types of cooking.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] The intention is to maintain the integrity of ingredients and achieve very precise control of cooking.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Although water is used in the method, only moisture in or added to the food bags is in contact with the food.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Meat has usually been cooked in water which is just simmering, such as in stewing; higher temperatures make meat tougher by causing the proteins to contract.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] With the adequate combination of temperature and cooking time, pathogens, such as bacteria will be killed, and pasteurization can be achieved.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Because browning (Maillard reactions) can only occur at higher temperatures (above the boiling point of water), these moist techniques do not develop the flavors associated with browning.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Meat will often undergo searing in a very hot pan, grilling or browning with a torch before moist cooking (though sometimes after).
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Thermostatically controlled methods, such as sous-vide, can also prevent overcooking by bringing the meat to the exact degree of doneness desired, and holding it at that temperature indefinitely.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] The combination of precise temperature control and long cooking duration makes it possible to be assured that pasteurization has been achieved, both on the surface and the interior of even very thick cuts of meat, which can not be assured with most other cooking techniques.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Beef can be cooked quickly at the table through several techniques.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] In hot pot cooking, such as shabu-shabu, very thinly sliced meat is cooked by the diners at the table by immersing it in a heated pot of water or stock with vegetables.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] In fondue bourguignonne, diners dip small pieces of beef into a pot of hot oil at the table.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Both techniques typically feature accompanying flavorful sauces to complement the meat.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Steak tartare is a French dish made from finely chopped or ground (minced) raw meat (often beef).
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] More accurately, it is scraped so as not to let even the slightest of the sinew fat get into the scraped meat.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] It is often served with onions, capers, seasonings such as fresh ground pepper and Worcestershire sauce, and sometimes raw egg yolk.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] The Belgian or Dutch dish *filet américain* is also made of finely chopped ground beef, though it is seasoned differently, and either eaten as a main dish or can be used as a dressing for a sandwich.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] *Kibbeh nayyeh* is a similar Lebanese and Syrian dish.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] And in Ethiopia, a ground raw meat dish called *tire siga* or *kitfo* is eaten (upon availability).
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Beef jerky is dried, salted, smoked beef popular in the United States.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Biltong is a cured, salted, air dried beef popular in South Africa.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Pastrami is often made from beef; raw beef is salted, then partly dried and seasoned with various herbs and spices, and smoked.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Corned beef is a cut of beef cured or pickled in a seasoned brine.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] The corn in *corned beef* refers to the grains of coarse salts (known as corns) used to cure it.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] The term *corned beef* can denote different styles of brine-cured beef, depending on the region.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Some, like American-style corned beef, are highly seasoned and often considered delicatessen fare.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Spiced beef is a cured and salted joint of round, topside, or silverside, traditionally served at Christmas in Ireland.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] It is a form of salt beef, cured with spices and saltpetre, intended to be boiled or broiled in Guinness or a similar stout, and then optionally roasted for a period after.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] There are various other recipes for pickled beef.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Beef is the third most widely consumed meat in the world, accounting for about 25% of meat production worldwide, after pork and poultry at 38% and 30% respectively.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Beef is a source of complete protein and it is a rich source (20% or more of the Daily Value, DV) of niacin, vitamin B12, iron and zinc.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] It contains high amounts of saturated fat.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Red meat is the most significant dietary source of carnitine and, like any other meat (pork, fish, veal, lamb etc.), is a source of creatine.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Creatine is converted to creatinine during cooking.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] According to the International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC), unprocessed red meat probably causes cancer, particularly colorectal cancer.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Studies have also linked red meat with higher risks of cardiovascular disease and type 2 diabetes.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] If meat is processed, such as by salting, curing, or smoking, health risks further increase.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] The IARC found "convincing" evidence that processed meat causes cancer in humans.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] The World Cancer Research Fund recommends limiting red meat to no more than three servings per week.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] A 2010 meta-analysis found that processed red meat (and all processed meat) was correlated with a higher risk of coronary heart disease, although based on studies that separated the two, this meta-analysis found that red meat intake was not associated with higher incidence of coronary heart disease.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] As of 2020, there is substantial evidence for a link between high consumption of processed red meat and coronary heart disease.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Some cattle raised in the United States feed on pastures fertilized with sewage sludge.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Elevated dioxins may be present in meat from these cattle.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] In 1984, the use of meat and bone meal in cattle feed resulted in the world's first outbreak of bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE or, colloquially, mad cow disease) in the United Kingdom.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] In 2010, the EU, through the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA), proposed a roadmap to gradually lift the restrictions on the feed ban.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] In 2013, the ban on feeding mammal-based products to cattle, was amended to allow for certain milk, fish, eggs, and plant-fed farm animal products to be used.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Most Indic religions reject the killing and eating of cows.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Hinduism prohibits the consumption of cow beef, known as *gomāṃsa* in Sanskrit.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Bovines have a sacred status in India especially the cow, due to their provision of sustenance for families.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Bovines are generally considered to be integral to the landscape.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] However, they do not consider the cow to be a god.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Many of India's rural economies depend on cattle farming; hence they have been revered in society.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Since the Vedic period, cattle, especially cows, were venerated as a source of milk, and dairy products, and their relative importance in transport services and farming like ploughing, row planting, ridging.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Veneration grew with the advent of Jainism and the Gupta period.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] In medieval India, Maharaja Ranjit Singh issued a proclamation on stopping cow slaughter.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Conflicts over cow slaughter often have sparked religious riots that have led to loss of human life and in one 1893 riot alone, more than 100 people were killed for the cause.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] For religious reasons, the ancient Egyptian priests also refrained from consuming beef.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Buddhists and Sikhs are also against wrongful slaughtering of animals, but they do not have a wrongful eating doctrine.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] In ancient China, the killing of cattle and consumption of beef was prohibited, as they were valued for their role in agriculture.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] This custom is still followed by a few Chinese families across the world.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] During the season of Lent, Orthodox Christians and Catholics periodically give up meat and poultry (and sometimes dairy products and eggs) as a religious act.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Observant Jews and Muslims may not eat any meat or poultry which has not been slaughtered and treated in conformance with religious laws.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Most of the North Indian states prohibit the killing of cow and consumption of beef for religious reasons.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Certain Hindu castes and sects continue to avoid beef from their diets.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Article 48 of the Constitution of India mandates the state may take steps for preserving and improving the bovine breeds, and prohibit the slaughter, of cows and calves and other milch and draught cattle.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] In 2017, a rule against the slaughter of cattle and the eating of beef was signed into law by presidential assent as a modified version of Prevention of Cruelty to Animals Act, 1960.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] The original act, however, did permit the humane slaughter of animals for use as food.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Existing meat export policy in India prohibits the export of beef (meat of cow, oxen and calf).
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Bone-in meat, a carcass, or half carcass of buffalo is also prohibited from export.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Only the boneless meat of buffalo, meat of goat and sheep and birds is permitted for export.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] In 2017, India sought a total "beef ban" and Australian market analysts predicted that this would create market opportunities for leather traders and meat producers there and elsewhere.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] Their prediction estimated a twenty percent shortage of beef and a thirteen percent shortage of leather in the world market.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] The cow is the national animal of Nepal, and slaughter of cattle is prohibited by law.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] In 2003, Cuba banned cow slaughter due to severe shortage of milk and milk products.
[src:danish-crown-company/beef] On 14 April 2021, the ban was loosened, allowing ranchers to do as they wish as long as state quotas were met and the health of the herd could be ensured.
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] During the Cold War, Boizenburg was part of East Germany, being located only about 7 km (4.3 mi) east of the Inner German Border (Iron Curtain).
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] The German name *Boyceneburg* was first documented in 1158.
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] The written form changed to *Boiceneburg* (1171) and then *Boizeneburg* (1195).
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] The old Low German name for the town and river (Boize) likely stems from the Slavic *boj* for war.
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] Boizenburg is, since 17 March 1939, officially called **Boizenburg/Elbe** to differentiate it from other settlements with similar names, primarily Boitzenburg in the Uckermark region.
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] The town has an area of 47.43 km2 (18.31 sq mi) and comprises 9 *ortsteile*: Bahlen, Bahlendorf, Gehrum, Gothmann, Heide, Metlitz, Schwartow, Streitheide, Vier.
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] Boizenburg is situated on the Boize river, with the old town being located between the Old and New Boize with a former moat.
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] To its north is mainland Mecklenburg while to its south lies the Elbe floodplain and, after the Sude canal, the Elbe itself.
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] The town borders Nostorf to the west, Schwanheide to the north-west, Gresse to the north, Neu Gülze and Teldau to the east, and Bleckede in the state of Lower Saxony to the south (mostly across the Elbe river).
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] The municipality of Teldau has an exclave to Boizenburg's south, resulting in the town only sharing a land border of only around 600 m (2,000 ft) instead of 1.75 km (1.09 mi) with Bleckede.
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] Boizenburg lies on the Berlin-Hamburg railway and is serviced by the RE1 between Hamburg and Rostock via the *Boizenburg (Elbe)* station.
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] The town is bypassed by the B5 to the north and the B195 federal road passes through the eastern part of the town, near the train station, from north to south.
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] The A24 federal highway is located roughly 22 km (14 mi) north of Boizenburg.
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] Boizenburg suffered during the Thirty Years' War, and its old castle was burnt down by Swedish troops in 1628.
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] In 1709, the church and 160 or more medieval dwellings were incinerated by a fire.
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] The Town Hall was rebuilt in 1712, and the layout of the town was redesigned by Prussian architects sent from Schwerin.
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] They focused on incorporating efficiency of movement with fire-resistance, better sanitation, and public space.
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] During the Napoleonic Wars, French troops were quartered in Boizenburg in 1807.
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] A battle was fought with the retreating French army near Boizenburg in 1813.
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] From 1815 to 1918, Boizenburg was part of the Grand Duchy of Mecklenburg-Schwerin.
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] In 1826, a highway was built, connecting Hamburg, Berlin, and subsequently Boizenburg (Highway "B5").
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] In 1846, the railway between Berlin and Hamburg was constructed.
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] Boizenburg was included with its own train station along this important route.
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] The shipbuilding yard Lemmsche founded in 1793 became highly industrialized in 1852 and produced many wooden and steel ships.
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] The shipbuilders Thomsen & Co supported the German war effort during World War II.
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] In 1973 the SED reactivated the shipbuilding facilities for the production of smaller inland ships for the USSR.
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] After being privatized in 1989, the yard was declared bankrupt in 1997.
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] Smaller, independent companies are active in the old shipyard.
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] The Boizenburg Tile Factory established by Hans Duensing in 1903, became Europe's largest tile manufacturer by 1937.
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] After being re-established in 1991, it remains one of the town's main employers.
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] Artistic impressions of the tile work produced in Boizenburg—particularly in the Art Nouveau style - can be found at the Erstes Deutsches Fliesen Museum.
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] Until 30 April 1945 a Nazi concentration camp was established in Boizenburg.
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] The camp was a subcamp to the Neuengamme concentration camp.
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] On 12 March 1953 a Royal Air Force Avro Lincoln heading to Berlin was shot down over Boizenburg by two Soviet Air Forces MiG-15 aircraft.
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] During the communist East German era, residents of Boizenburg were kept under close scrutiny by the Stasi.
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] Many deemed "politically untrustworthy" had their property confiscated during a state-sponsored terror campaign code-named Operation Vermin.
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] Boizenburg is, despite not being a part of it itself, the seat of the nearby Amt Boizenburg-Land.
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] One of the advantages of Boizenburg's isolation during the Cold War is the pristine natural landscape of the Elbe Valley region stretching to the north, south and east.
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] Much of the architecture and infrastructure in the old city remained 'perfectly untouched' during the DDR regime.
[src:danish-crown-company/boizenburg] In addition to significant restoration projects, new installations such as the modern redesign of the harbor and the addition of a topiary garden have greatly added to the old town's charm.
[src:danish-crown-company/bonnétable] Bonnétable is twinned with Horncastle in rural Lincolnshire.
[src:danish-crown-company/bonnétable] The towns' relationship is commemorated by a *Rue Horncastle* in Bonnétable, and a *Bonnetable*(*sic*; no acute accent on the e)*Road* in Horncastle.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] A **butcher** is a tradesperson who specializes in meatcutting, breaking down animal carcasses into primal cuts, preparation and retailing of meat, and sometimes slaughtering animals, or participates within any combination of these tasks.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] They may prepare standard cuts of meat and poultry for sale in retail or wholesale food establishments.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] A butcher may be employed by supermarkets, grocery stores, butcher shops and fish markets, slaughterhouses, or may be self-employed.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Butchery is an ancient trade, whose duties may date back to the domestication of livestock; butchering guilds were first formed in England as far back as 1272.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] In England during the Middle Ages, butchering was heavily regulated and structured.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Butchers operated in a broad network of urban trade systems, some of these were food provision, textiles, clothing, etc.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] These trades overlapped and allowed for interconnected systems to form in medieval towns.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] The different trade regulations maintained the quality of meat and protect the public.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] The butchering was regulated by appointed officials, specifically when it came to the sale and preparation of the meat.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] These regulations were used to make sure they met the standards to be sold to the public.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] These regulations represent earlier efforts to maintain quality standards in public spaces and markets.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Despite earlier attempts and regulations, butchers were still associated with air contamination and ‘putrid’ meat.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Historical accounts commonly show a similar complaint of butchers disposing of the waste of their butchering into public spaces.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] These complaints linked the disposal of the waste to diseases and bad smells.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Authorities took these disposals as serious offences and were punished accordingly.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] These punishments were to deter such practices, and contributed to restricting instances of improper disposal.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] When they would occur, they were sometimes associated to widespread animal diseases when it became difficult to ensure the quality of meat.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Through medieval England to the Renaissance, the butchering trade became closely tied to guilds systems in urban communities.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Guilds played a big role in regulations and market organization and economic activity.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] They often played bigger roles in bigger urban settings such as cities or large towns.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] During this period, efforts were made to regulate and standardize the butchering trade.Authorities also became more involved in the regulation of guilds and butchering to ensure they continued to perform with quality in mind.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] The authorities would be very involved in making sure that underweighting of the meat would not occur, so the price of the meat would be fair to the public.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] This caused tension between the butchers and regulators, especially in times of changing market conditions.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] By the nineteenth century, industrialisation brought major changes to the meat industry and the butchering profession.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Slaughterhouses increasingly located to designated industrial facilities away from public spaces.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Prior to this shift butchering was typical to see in public.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] This caused a bigger rift between butchering and the public, as it was starting to no longer be popular to go to butcher shops nor see the process of the butchering.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Industrial facilities were often seen as more sanitary, as they were seen to have more regulations.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] This led to the foundation of what we now know today of the relationships between the meat industry, butchers, and the public.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Since the 20th century, many countries and local jurisdictions offer trade certifications for butchers to ensure quality, safety, and health standards but not all butchers have formal certification or training.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Trade qualification in English-speaking countries is often earned through an apprenticeship although some training organisations also certify their students.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] In Canada, once a butcher is trade qualified, they can learn to become a master butcher (Fleishmaster).
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Standards and practices of butchery differ between countries, regions and ethnic groups.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Variation with respect to the types of animals that are butchered as well as the cuts and parts of the animal that are sold depends on the types of foods that are prepared by the butcher's customers.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] In the industrialized world, slaughterhouses use butchers to slaughter the animals, performing one or a few of the steps repeatedly as specialists on a semi-automated disassembly line.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Secondary butchery involves boning, trimming and value-adding of primal cuts in preparation for sale.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Historically, primary and secondary butchery were performed in the same establishment, but the advent of methods of preservation (vacuum packing) and low cost transportation has largely separated them.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] In parts of the world, it is common for butchers to perform many or all of the butcher's duties.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Where refrigeration is less common, these skills are required to sell the meat of slaughtered animals.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Butchers sell their goods in specialized stores, commonly termed a butcher shop (American English), butchery (South African English) or butchers (British English).
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Butchers at a butcher shop may perform primary butchery, but will typically perform secondary butchery to prepare fresh cuts of meat for sale.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] These shops may also sell related products, such as Charcuterie, hot food (using their own meat products), food preparation supplies, baked goods and grocery items.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Butcher shops can have a wider variety of animal types, meat cuts and quality of cuts.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Additionally, butcher shops may focus on a particular culture, or nationality, of meat production.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Some butcher shops, termed "meat delis", may also include a delicatessen.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] In the United States and Canada, butcher shops have become less common because of the increasing popularity of supermarkets and warehouse clubs.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Many remaining ones are aimed at Hispanic and other immigrants or, more recently, those looking for organic offerings.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Supermarkets employ butchers for secondary butchery, but in the United States even that role is diminished with the advent of "case-ready" meat, where the product is packaged for retail sale at the packinghouse or specialized central processing plants.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Hot boning is a process used by butchers to remove the meat from the carcass almost instantly after the animal is slaughtered.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] This is done to prevent rigor mortis (Chemical changes causing stiffening of the limbs and corpse).
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Warm meat is often softer and easier to remove from the bone, and hot boning can save refrigeration costs.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Cattle, Lamb, and Pigs are the animals most frequently hot boned.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Popularity and relevance of the art of butchering have shifted over the years both geographically and historically.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Meat demand has risen dramatically over the centuries, but in many Western countries, like the United States, Butcher shops are less prevalent.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Meat markets have grown by an average 5.1% per year since 1970, and this is largely due to urbanization and demand.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] In the United States, meat is mass-produced and then shipped to stores that can sell large amounts quickly and keep the meat frozen.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Individual butcher shops with contracts to small farms struggle to keep their prices low enough to match large industries.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Butcher shops are still common in many European and South American countries.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] In countries like Argentina meat consumption was as high as 97 kilograms per person in 2002, with the vast majority of it being beef.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] In asian countries, butchering consists of more "nose to tail" butchering practices, which involves using every part of the animal, including common parts that are typically thrown away in the West, like pig blood, chicken feet, rabbit head, tripe, and tendon.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Often these meats are harvested with specialty knives like the Caidao, hankatsu, and honesuki.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] In the United States and in other western countries, many customers have become familiar with meat departments in grocery stores and supermarkets rather than butcher shops.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Meat departments are used to sell and take in more product faster and more efficiently.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Butchers who work in meat departments have tasks like small scale cutting and cleaning, as well as marinating, packaging and ordering shipments of meat.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Butchers in meat departments almost never assist in the slaughtering process.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Most meat departments sell fresh (never frozen) cuts of meat.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Many butchers are able to manipulate the "bloom" aspect of meat (the bright red color of steaks that looks fresh).
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] When meat is first cut, it will appear purple.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] This is due to a surplus of myoglobin on the surface; once the meat has first warmed up to room temperature, oxygen is added to the meat to oxidize myoglobin, which produces oxymyoglobin, giving the meat the scarlet red color that consumers indicate as fresh.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Through this process, supermarkets and meat departments are able to make meat appear fresh for longer periods of time.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] This process is referred to as "blooming".
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] A primal cut is a piece of meat initially separated from the carcass during butchering.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] Different countries and cultures make these cuts in different ways, and primal cuts also differ between type of carcass.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] The British, American and French primal cuts all differ in some respects.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] One notable example with pork is fatback, which in Europe is an important primal cut of pork, but in North America is regarded as trimmings to be used in sausage or rendered into lard.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] The primal cuts may be sold complete or cut further.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] In various periods and cultures, the term "butcher" has been applied to people who act cruelly to other human beings or slaughter them.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] For example, Pompey, a prominent Roman general and politician of the first century BC, got the Latin nickname *adulescentulus carnifex*, translated as "The Teenage Butcher" or "The Butcher Boy", due to brutal treatment of political opponents in the early part of his career.
[src:danish-crown-company/butcher] More recently, the Bosslot Serb war criminal Ratko Mladić was nicknamed "the Butcher of the Balkans".
[src:danish-crown-company/danish-crown-company] The Danish Crown group is owned by 5,620 Danish farmers, and annually the group is part of 49 billion meals for consumers worldwide.
[src:danish-crown-company/danish-crown-company] The group has a turnover of approximately DKK 60 billion kroner and employs approximately 26,600 employees across 89 production sites, 40 warehouses and 38 offices across 30 countries.
[src:danish-crown-company/danish-crown-company] The group is the world's largest pork exporter and Europe's largest producer of pork.
[src:danish-crown-company/danish-crown-company] The Danish Crown group is also Europe's largest meat processing company.
[src:danish-crown-company/danish-crown-company] In the financial year 2020–21, Danish Crown's exports amounted to DKK 24 billion kroner.
[src:danish-crown-company/danish-crown-company] This corresponds to approximately 20% of Danish food exports and approximately 3% of Danish merchandise exports.
[src:danish-crown-company/danish-crown-company] The first Danish cooperative pig abattoir was established in Horsens, Denmark in 1887.
[src:danish-crown-company/danish-crown-company] In the following 40–50 years, a large number of cooperative pig abattoirs were established across the country.
[src:danish-crown-company/danish-crown-company] In 1960, the cooperative abattoirs began to merge in order to better have the strength to carry out the tasks with, among other things, sales, marketing and product development.
[src:danish-crown-company/danish-crown-company] In 1990, Danish Crown was established as a fusion of Wenbo, Østjyske and Tulip Food Company (which included Horsens Andels-Svineslagteri from 1887), and in 1994, Slagteri Syd was merged in.
[src:danish-crown-company/danish-crown-company] In 1998, Danish Crown and Vestjyske Slagterier merged.
[src:danish-crown-company/danish-crown-company] In April 2002, the Danish Competition Council gave permission for a merger between Danish Crown and Steff Houlberg, and a large part of the original cooperative pig abattoirs is part of the new Danish Crown.
[src:danish-crown-company/danish-crown-company] On 13 October 2010, the shareholders decided to transfer the activities to a limited company, Danish Crown A/S formerly Danish Crown Holding A/S.
[src:danish-crown-company/danish-crown-company] The co-operatives retained ownership through the co-operative, which is now called the Danish Crown Amba Supply Company.
[src:danish-crown-company/danish-crown-company] The limited company was originally established on 1 July 2001.
